biomarkers.name: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgA
biomarkers.more_info: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgA is a marker used to identify active Helicobacter pylori infections. Its presence in the blood indicates a localized mucosal immune response, which can be a sign of ongoing bacterial activity in the gastrointestinal tract.

biomarkers.name: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgG
biomarkers.more_info: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgG is an immunoglobulin marker used to detect chronic Helicobacter pylori infections. Elevated levels of this antibody can indicate a prolonged immune response to the bacteria, which is associated with gastrointestinal issues such as gastritis and peptic ulcers.

biomarkers.name: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgM
biomarkers.more_info: Anti H.Pylori Ab-IgM is an early-stage antibody produced during an initial Helicobacter pylori infection. Elevated levels suggest recent exposure to the bacteria and can help differentiate between acute and chronic infections.

biomarkers.name: HBs Antibody
biomarkers.more_info: HBs Antibody (Hepatitis B Surface Antibody) is a marker of immunity against hepatitis B. It can develop after recovery from infection or following successful vaccination.

biomarkers.name: HBs Antigen
biomarkers.more_info: HBs Antigen (Hepatitis B Surface Antigen) is a protein found on the surface of the hepatitis B virus. Its presence in the blood indicates an active hepatitis B infection and potential infectivity.

biomarkers.name: HCV Antibody
biomarkers.more_info: HCV Antibody is used to screen for exposure to the hepatitis C virus. A positive result indicates prior or current infection, which requires follow-up tests to assess active viral presence.

biomarkers.name: HIV P24 Ag
biomarkers.more_info: HIV P24 Ag is an antigen test used to detect the p24 protein, an early marker of HIV infection. It is particularly useful in identifying acute or early-stage HIV before antibodies are detectable.

biomarkers.name: HIV1,2 Ab
biomarkers.more_info: HIV1,2 Ab refers to antibodies against Human Immunodeficiency Virus types 1 and 2. The presence of these antibodies indicates exposure to the virus and potential infection, requiring further evaluation to confirm HIV status.

biomarkers.name: Appearance
biomarkers.more_info: The appearance of urine, whether clear or cloudy, helps identify potential issues. Cloudy urine may indicate infections, high protein levels, or the presence of crystals.

biomarkers.name: Blood (Hemoglobin)
biomarkers.more_info: The presence of blood or hemoglobin in urine (hematuria) may indicate kidney stones, infections, trauma, or other urological conditions.

biomarkers.name: Casts /h.p.f
biomarkers.more_info: Casts are cylindrical particles formed in the kidney tubules. Their presence may indicate kidney disease, infection, or other renal conditions.

biomarkers.name: Color
biomarkers.more_info: Urine color is assessed to evaluate hydration status and detect potential abnormalities. Variations in color can indicate conditions such as dehydration, hematuria, or liver disease.

biomarkers.name: Crystals
biomarkers.more_info: Crystals in urine can indicate metabolic conditions or a risk for kidney stone formation. The type of crystals provides clues about underlying disorders.

biomarkers.name: Ep.Cells /h.p.f
biomarkers.more_info: Epithelial cells (Ep.Cells) in urine are normal in small numbers, but increased amounts may indicate contamination, infection, or kidney disease.

biomarkers.name: Glucose
biomarkers.more_info: The presence of glucose in urine (glucosuria) is often a sign of diabetes or hyperglycemia and warrants further investigation.

biomarkers.name: Mucus
biomarkers.more_info: Mucus in urine is usually normal in small amounts, but excessive mucus may indicate irritation or inflammation of the urinary tract.

biomarkers.name: Nitrite
biomarkers.more_info: Nitrite in urine is a marker for bacterial infections, particularly urinary tract infections caused by nitrate-reducing bacteria.

biomarkers.name: pH
biomarkers.more_info: Urine pH indicates its acidity or alkalinity. Abnormal values may suggest metabolic or renal conditions, such as acidosis, alkalosis, or infection.

biomarkers.name: Protein
biomarkers.more_info: The presence of protein in urine (proteinuria) can indicate kidney dysfunction, hypertension, or other systemic conditions like diabetes.

biomarkers.name: R.B.C /h.p.f
biomarkers.more_info: Red blood cells (R.B.C) in urine suggest bleeding in the urinary tract, which may be caused by infections, stones, or trauma.

biomarkers.name: Urobilinogen
biomarkers.more_info: Urobilinogen in urine reflects liver function and bile flow. Elevated levels may indicate liver disease, hemolysis, or bile duct obstruction.

biomarkers.name: W.B.C /h.p.f
biomarkers.more_info: White blood cells (W.B.C) in urine indicate inflammation or infection in the urinary tract, kidneys, or bladder.

biomarkers.name: Yeast
biomarkers.more_info: Yeast in urine may indicate a fungal infection, commonly seen in immunocompromised individuals or those with poorly controlled diabetes.

biomarkers.name: BMI
biomarkers.more_info: Body Mass Index (BMI) is a calculated value that assesses body weight in relation to height. It is used to classify individuals as underweight, normal weight, overweight, or obese, providing insight into overall health and disease risk.

biomarkers.name: BUN
biomarkers.more_info: BUN measures the amount of nitrogen in your blood that comes from urea, a waste product of protein metabolism. Since the kidneys filter urea from the bloodstream, this value is an important indicator of kidney function. Abnormal BUN levels can point to issues such as kidney dysfunction, dehydration, or liver disorders.

biomarkers.name: BUN/Creatinine
biomarkers.more_info: This value represents the calculated ratio between BUN and creatinine levels in your blood. It is used to provide additional context regarding kidney function by comparing these two waste products. The ratio helps differentiate between various causes of kidney impairment, as different conditions may alter BUN and creatinine levels in distinct ways.

biomarkers.name: Calcium (Ca)
biomarkers.more_info: Calcium is an essential mineral for bone health, muscle function, and nerve signaling. Abnormal levels may indicate parathyroid disorders, bone diseases, or kidney problems.

biomarkers.name: Calculated Serum Osmolality
biomarkers.more_info: Calculated serum osmolality estimates the concentration of solutes in the blood, helping to evaluate hydration status and electrolyte balance.

biomarkers.name: Creatinine
biomarkers.more_info: Creatinine is a byproduct of muscle metabolism, and its levels are used to assess kidney function. Since creatinine is filtered by the kidneys, its serum concentration provides insight into how well the kidneys are removing waste. Elevated levels may indicate impaired kidney function, while lower levels can be seen in individuals with reduced muscle mass.

biomarkers.name: Direct Bilirubin
biomarkers.more_info: Direct bilirubin measures the conjugated form of bilirubin, which is processed by the liver. High levels are often associated with liver disease or bile duct blockages.

biomarkers.name: eGFR
biomarkers.more_info: Estimated Glomerular Filtration Rate (eGFR) evaluates kidney function and is used to stage chronic kidney disease. Lower values indicate reduced kidney function.

biomarkers.name: FBS
biomarkers.more_info: Fasting Blood Sugar (FBS) measures the glucose level in the blood after an overnight fast. It is a key marker for diagnosing diabetes or prediabetes and assessing glucose metabolism.

biomarkers.name: Gamma GT
biomarkers.more_info: Gamma-Glutamyl Transferase (Gamma GT) is an enzyme associated with the liver and bile ducts. Elevated levels are commonly seen in liver disease, bile duct obstruction, or excessive alcohol consumption.

biomarkers.name: Iron (Fe)
biomarkers.more_info: Iron is crucial for hemoglobin production and oxygen transport in the blood. Low levels can indicate anemia, while high levels may suggest iron overload or metabolic issues.

biomarkers.name: Iron Binding Capacity (TIBC)
biomarkers.more_info: Iron Binding Capacity (TIBC) measures the blood's capacity to bind iron with transferrin. It helps evaluate iron status and is often used to diagnose anemia or iron overload conditions.

biomarkers.name: Magnesium (Mg)
biomarkers.more_info: Magnesium is an essential mineral for muscle and nerve function, as well as energy production. Abnormal levels can affect heart rhythm, muscle function, and overall metabolism.

biomarkers.name: Phosphatase Alkaline
biomarkers.more_info: Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP) is an enzyme linked to the liver, bile ducts, and bones. Elevated levels can indicate liver disease, bile duct blockage, or bone disorders.

biomarkers.name: Phosphorus (P)
biomarkers.more_info: Phosphorus is vital for bone and teeth formation, energy metabolism, and cell function. Abnormal levels may signal kidney disease or issues with calcium and vitamin D metabolism.

biomarkers.name: Potassium (K)
biomarkers.more_info: Potassium is an essential electrolyte for heart, muscle, and nerve function. Abnormal levels can affect cardiac rhythm and muscle performance.

biomarkers.name: S.G.O.T (AST)
biomarkers.more_info: Serum Glutamic Oxaloacetic Transaminase (AST) is an enzyme found in the liver and other tissues. Elevated levels may indicate liver damage, muscle injury, or other conditions affecting these organs.

biomarkers.name: Sodium (Na)
biomarkers.more_info: Sodium is a key electrolyte that helps maintain fluid balance and proper nerve and muscle function. Abnormal levels can indicate dehydration, kidney issues, or hormonal imbalances.

biomarkers.name: TG / HDL Ratio
biomarkers.more_info: The Triglyceride to HDL Cholesterol (TG/HDL) ratio is used to assess cardiovascular risk. A higher ratio is associated with an increased risk of atherosclerosis and heart disease.

biomarkers.name: Total Bilirubin
biomarkers.more_info: Total bilirubin measures the amount of bilirubin in the blood, including both direct and indirect forms. Elevated levels may indicate liver dysfunction, hemolysis, or bile duct obstruction.

biomarkers.name: Uric Acid
biomarkers.more_info: Uric acid is a byproduct of purine metabolism. Elevated levels can cause gout and kidney stones or indicate other metabolic disorders like hyperuricemia.

biomarkers.name: VLDL/TG Ratio
biomarkers.more_info: The VLDL to Triglyceride (VLDL/TG) ratio helps evaluate the efficiency of lipid metabolism. Abnormal values may suggest metabolic disorders.

biomarkers.name: Zinc (Zn)
biomarkers.more_info: Zinc is a trace element critical for immune function, wound healing, and enzyme activity. Abnormal levels may affect immunity, growth, or metabolic functions.

biomarkers.name: CA 19-9
biomarkers.more_info: CA 19-9 is a tumor marker primarily associated with pancreatic, gastrointestinal, and bile duct cancers. Elevated levels may indicate malignancy or inflammation in the gastrointestinal system.

biomarkers.name: CEA (Carcinoembryonic Ag)
biomarkers.more_info: CEA, or Carcinoembryonic Antigen, is a tumor marker used primarily to monitor colorectal cancer and other malignancies. Elevated levels may indicate cancer presence or recurrence, though it can also be elevated in non-cancerous conditions.

biomarkers.name: P.S.A .Free (PSA.F)
biomarkers.more_info: Free Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA_F) is the unbound form of PSA in the blood. The ratio of free to total PSA is used to differentiate between benign and malignant prostate conditions.

biomarkers.name: P.S.A .Total (PSA.T)
biomarkers.more_info: Total Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA.T) is a protein produced by the prostate gland. Elevated levels may indicate prostate cancer, benign prostatic hyperplasia, or inflammation of the prostate.

biomarkers.name: Cholesterol Total
biomarkers.more_info: Total cholesterol is the overall amount of cholesterol in the blood, including low-density lipoprotein (LDL) and high-density lipoprotein (HDL). It is an essential marker for evaluating the risk of cardiovascular disease. Levels above the recommended range may indicate an increased risk of heart problems.

biomarkers.name: Cholesterol/HDL Ratio
biomarkers.more_info: The Total Cholesterol/HDL ratio compares the amount of total cholesterol to HDL cholesterol in the blood. A lower ratio indicates a healthier balance and reduced cardiovascular risk. It is a useful marker for assessing overall heart health.

biomarkers.name: HDL Cholestrol
biomarkers.more_info: HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein) cholesterol is often called 'good' cholesterol because it helps remove other forms of cholesterol from the bloodstream. Higher levels of HDL are associated with a lower risk of heart disease. Maintaining healthy HDL levels supports cardiovascular health.

biomarkers.name: LDL Cholesterol
biomarkers.more_info: LDL (Low-Density Lipoprotein) cholesterol is known as 'bad' cholesterol because it can build up in the walls of arteries, leading to plaque formation. High levels increase the risk of atherosclerosis and cardiovascular disease. Monitoring LDL levels is crucial for heart health.

biomarkers.name: LDL/HDL Ratio
biomarkers.more_info: The LDL to HDL Cholesterol (LDL/HDL) ratio is a marker for cardiovascular health. A lower ratio is desirable as it indicates a healthier lipid profile.

biomarkers.name: Non HDL Cholesterol
biomarkers.more_info: Non-HDL cholesterol represents the total 'bad' cholesterol in your blood by subtracting HDL (the 'good' cholesterol) from your total cholesterol. This value includes LDL, VLDL, and other atherogenic particles that can contribute to plaque buildup in the arteries. Monitoring and managing non-HDL cholesterol levels is important for assessing cardiovascular risk and supporting overall heart health.

biomarkers.name: CRP (Titer)
biomarkers.more_info: C-reactive protein (CRP) is a marker of inflammation in the body. Elevated levels can indicate acute or chronic inflammatory conditions, infections, or autoimmune diseases. The titer measurement helps assess the severity of inflammation.

biomarkers.name: RF
biomarkers.more_info: Rheumatoid Factor (RF) is an antibody associated with autoimmune disorders, particularly rheumatoid arthritis. Elevated levels are often seen in individuals with inflammatory joint diseases or other autoimmune conditions.

biomarkers.name: Eos#
biomarkers.more_info: Eosinophils (Eos#) are white blood cells involved in allergic responses and fighting parasitic infections. Elevated levels are often associated with allergies, asthma, or parasitic infections.

biomarkers.name: ESR 1st hr
biomarkers.more_info: Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) measures the rate at which red blood cells settle in a tube over one hour. It is a nonspecific marker of inflammation, infection, or autoimmune conditions.

biomarkers.name: Hematocrit (Hct)
biomarkers.more_info: Hematocrit (Hct) represents the percentage of blood volume occupied by red blood cells. Abnormal values may indicate anemia, dehydration, or other conditions.

biomarkers.name: Hemoglobin (Hb)
biomarkers.more_info: Hemoglobin (Hb) is a protein in red blood cells responsible for oxygen transport. Low levels indicate anemia, while high levels may suggest polycythemia or other conditions.

biomarkers.name: Lymp#
biomarkers.more_info: Lymphocytes (Lymp#) are white blood cells that are part of the immune system, helping fight viral infections and producing antibodies. Abnormal levels may indicate infections, immune disorders, or lymphoproliferative diseases.

biomarkers.name: M.C.H
biomarkers.more_info: Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin (MCH) measures the average amount of hemoglobin in a red blood cell. Abnormal values help diagnose types of anemia.

biomarkers.name: M.C.H.C
biomarkers.more_info: Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin Concentration (MCHC) measures the average concentration of hemoglobin in red blood cells. It helps evaluate the type and severity of anemia.

biomarkers.name: M.C.V
biomarkers.more_info: Mean Corpuscular Volume (MCV) measures the average size of red blood cells. It is used to classify anemias as microcytic, normocytic, or macrocytic.

biomarkers.name: Mono#
biomarkers.more_info: Monocytes (Monor) are a type of white blood cell involved in removing debris and fighting infections. Elevated levels may indicate chronic inflammation or certain infections.

biomarkers.name: MPV
biomarkers.more_info: Mean Platelet Volume (MPV) measures the average size of platelets. Larger platelets may indicate increased platelet production, while smaller ones may suggest certain platelet disorders.

biomarkers.name: Neut#
biomarkers.more_info: Neutrophils (Neut#) are a type of white blood cell that plays a critical role in fighting bacterial and fungal infections. Elevated or decreased levels can indicate infection or immune system issues.

biomarkers.name: PCT
biomarkers.more_info: Plateletcrit (PCT) is a measure of the volume occupied by platelets in the blood, used to assess overall platelet mass.

biomarkers.name: PDW
biomarkers.more_info: Platelet Distribution Width (PDW) measures the variation in platelet size, which can indicate platelet activation or disorders.

biomarkers.name: Platelets (Plt)
biomarkers.more_info: Platelet count measures the number of platelets in the blood, which are essential for blood clotting. Abnormal levels may indicate clotting disorders or bone marrow issues.

biomarkers.name: R.B.C
biomarkers.more_info: Red Blood Cell (RBC) count measures the number of red blood cells in the blood. It helps assess oxygen transport capacity and can indicate anemia or polycythemia.

biomarkers.name: RDW
biomarkers.more_info: Red Cell Distribution Width (RDW) measures the variation in size of red blood cells. Increased RDW can indicate anemia or other blood disorders.

biomarkers.name: Transferrin Saturation
biomarkers.more_info: Transferrin saturation indicates the percentage of transferrin—the main protein responsible for transporting iron in the blood—that is bound with iron. This metric is crucial for evaluating iron metabolism, as low levels can suggest iron deficiency while high levels may point to conditions like iron overload. Monitoring transferrin saturation helps in diagnosing and managing various iron-related disorders, ensuring proper oxygen delivery and overall metabolic balance.

biomarkers.name: WBC
biomarkers.more_info: White Blood Cell (WBC) count measures the number of white blood cells in the blood, which are essential for fighting infections and responding to inflammation.

biomarkers.name: Ferritin
biomarkers.more_info: Ferritin is a protein that stores and releases iron in the body. Measuring ferritin levels helps assess total body iron stores, with low levels indicating iron deficiency and high levels suggesting overload or inflammation.

biomarkers.name: Folic Acid (Vit B9)
biomarkers.more_info: Folic Acid, or Vitamin B9, is essential for DNA synthesis, red blood cell production, and neural health. Low levels can lead to anemia, neural tube defects during pregnancy, and other health issues.

biomarkers.name: Total Body Iron Storage
biomarkers.more_info: Total body iron storage represents the overall iron reserves in the body, including ferritin and hemosiderin. It is crucial for evaluating iron balance and diagnosing conditions like anemia or hemochromatosis.

biomarkers.name: Vitamin B12 (Cobalamin) -
biomarkers.more_info: Vitamin B12, also known as Cobalamin, is crucial for nerve function, red blood cell formation, and DNA synthesis. Deficiency can lead to megaloblastic anemia, neurological issues, and fatigue.

biomarkers.name: Vitamin D (25 OH)
biomarkers.more_info: Vitamin D (25 OH) is a marker for assessing vitamin D levels in the body, which are essential for bone health, immune function, and calcium metabolism. Deficiency can lead to bone disorders such as rickets or osteomalacia.

biomarkers.name: Hb A1C
biomarkers.more_info: HbA1c measures the percentage of glycated hemoglobin in the blood, reflecting the average blood glucose levels over the past two to three months. It is a crucial test for managing diabetes, indicating how well blood sugar levels have been controlled. Higher HbA1c levels suggest poorer glucose control and an increased risk of diabetes complications, while lower HbA1c levels indicate better glucose management.

biomarkers.name: HOMA-IR
biomarkers.more_info: The Homeostatic Model Assessment for Insulin Resistance (HOMA-IR) is a calculated marker that assesses insulin resistance and beta-cell function. It is a key indicator of metabolic health and diabetes risk.

biomarkers.name: Insulin
biomarkers.more_info: Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that regulates blood sugar levels by facilitating glucose uptake into cells. High or low levels may indicate insulin resistance, diabetes, or other metabolic disorders.

biomarkers.name: TSH
biomarkers.more_info: TSH (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone) is a pituitary hormone that regulates the production of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). It is a primary marker for detecting thyroid dysfunction, including hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. Abnormal TSH levels prompt further thyroid testing.
